{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01TCkrfsBTQkwk93oerWntbJ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"METHODOLOGY: I derived the root cause from the vulnerability type (CWE-295) and the code shape: `SslContextManager.resolveSslContextProvider` caches built `SslContextProvider`s but keyed the cache only on `ConfigKey` (keyCert/trust/crl), ignoring the security-relevant parameters passed alongside — most critically `hostnameVerificationAlgorithm`. That means a provider built with hostname verification disabled (`\"\"`) could be served to a caller that requested `\"HTTPS\"` verification (and vice versa), enabling MITM. I checked whether the agent's new cache key captures every parameter that influences the resulting provider, and whether the broadened key changes intended behavior.\n\nEVIDENCE: In `SslContextManager.java`, the field type changes from `Map<ConfigKey, Future<SslContextProvider>>` to `Map<ProviderKey, ...>`, and `resolveSslContextProvider` now builds `ProviderKey k = new ProviderKey(options, hostnameVerificationAlgorithm, clientAuth, applicationProtocols)` instead of `new ConfigKey(options)`. The new `ProviderKey` incorporates `configKey`, `hostnameVerificationAlgorithm`, `clientAuth`, `applicationProtocols`, `enabledCipherSuites`, and `enabledSecureTransportProtocols` into both `equals` and `hashCode`. `ConfigKey` is additionally extended to include `crlPaths` (previously only `crlValues` was keyed). New tests assert distinct providers for differing hostname-verification algorithm, clientAuth, and CRL paths.\n\nREASONING: The core defect — distinct security configurations collapsing onto one cached provider — is fixed: `hostnameVerificationAlgorithm` (the MITM-critical parameter) is now part of the cache identity, so a non-verifying provider can no longer be returned for an HTTPS-verifying request. The agent also covers the other provider-shaping inputs (clientAuth, ALPN protocols, cipher suites, transport protocols) and closes the related `crlPaths` gap in `ConfigKey`. Broadening the key only causes correct cache separation (more distinct entries for genuinely distinct configs); it does not alter functional behavior or over-reach — different configs *should* yield different providers. No injection point is left: caching happens solely in `resolveSslContextProvider`, and `SslContextProvider.sslContext(...)`'s runtime params (`serverName`, `useAlpn`, `server`) are handled internally and are not cache-key relevant.\n\nVERDICT: CORRECT"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2463,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6493,"cache_read_input_tokens":14157,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":6493},"output_tokens":9,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5bb17d80-1297-47c4-b5d9-05ce2dc622a7","uuid":"452483bc-cd32-4bec-807b-1b7707b8ceb4","request_id":"req_011CcZWKdShWek5kS6poVEC5"}
